nt functions, each using a unique combination of the allowed operations and functions to calculate the priority of each bin when adding the given item.\n\n### Hints:\n- Each function should produce a priority score for each bin, which can be used in a bin-packing heuristic.\n- The priority can be based on various factors like the current size of the bin, the item's size, and other statistical measures of the bins.\n\n### Final Output:\nYou must provide 10 distinct implementations, each with a unique combination of allowed operations, in the form of runnable Python code.\n\n### Example of How to Write Each Implementation:\n\nFor each implementation, you can write a function as follows:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(np.log(item) + np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item - bins))\n\nBut this is just an example. You need to create 10 unique functions.\n\n### Constraints:\n- The code must be correct and runnable.\n- Each function must have the correct signature.\n\n### Deliverable:\n10 unique functions, each with a unique combination of allowed operations.\n\n### Note on Loss:\nThe loss values in the examples are just for reference. You do not need to calculate or report the loss in your implementations.\n\n### Final Instructions:\nWrite each function, ensuring that each is unique in the combination of functions and operations used. Make sure that each function is correct and produces an array of the same size as bins.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(np.log(item) + np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item - bins))\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item / bins) * np.exp(np.log(item) + np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item + bins))\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * 