lace the item in the bin that would leave the most space (useful for small items).\n- Random Fit: Place the item in a randomly selected bin that can fit it.\n\nBut for this task, you need to create a priority function that uses mathematical operations to compute a priority score for each bin.\n\n### Final Instructions:\n- Implement 10 unique priority functions.\n- Each function must be correct and use only allowed operations.\n- Each function must be a separate code block.\n- Do not include any additional text or explanations.\n- The code must be runnable as is.\n\n### Final Example of a Correct Function:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.sqrt(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\nThis function uses a combination of mathematical operations to compute the priority score for each bin.\n</think>\n\nHere are 10 unique implementations of the `priority` function, each using a different combination of allowed operations to compute the priority scores for bin packing:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nimport math\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.max(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(bins - item)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.sqrt(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item + 1) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(bins - item)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item / (item + np.mean(bins))) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(bins - item)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.sqrt(bins)) * np.log(item + bins) + np.cos(bins - item)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.max(bins)) * np.log(item + bins) + np.sin(bins - item)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) 